  "description": "¶What this lesson covers Why and how Peirce\u0026rsquo;s semiotic theory invites mathematical formalization, which mathematical structures correspond to which semiotic concepts, and what is gained by making the correspondence precise.\n¶Prerequisites Signs and Interpretants, Semiosis and Sign Processes. Familiarity with Heyting algebras, closure operators and fixed points, and typed lambda calculus is helpful but not required — the lesson motivates why those structures appear.\n¶Why formalize signs? Peirce\u0026rsquo;s semiotics is already structured. The sign relation is triadic. Signs fall into classifications (icon/index/symbol, qualisign/sinsign/legisign, rheme/dicisign/argument). Semiosis is iterative — interpretants become signs for further interpretation. These are not vague observations but descriptions of a structured process. The question is whether that structure can be made mathematically precise, and what precision buys.\n",
  "keywords": "semiotics, mathematics",
  "name": "From Signs to Formal Structure",
